Comment: and a common follow-up to the position
This being one of the first games that I had started in the tournament, I wanted to get out of the line of the sample game. This prepares to get rid of a future Ne5...
I wonder whether 10...f6 would have been better here? Perhaps not, since 11.Nxc6 bxc6 weakens Black's queenside pawns... Besides, this move does turn out just fine for Black
Black now has a little more confidence to start activity queenside!
Black now has a little more confidence to start activity queenside!
Moving the knight to a more active position
! not a bad move at all! This move opens up the position on the kingside, and both of White's bishops look intimidating at where they lie.
having identified no threats to the Black position, Black pushes on queenside
It was better to allow White to exchange pawns than it was for Black; after 13...dxe4 14.Bxe4 White gets a tempo attack on my knight
Black didn't mind this pawn excahnge too much - now the light-square bishop can get into the action kingside...

!? Speaking of light square bishops... White's first sac. I had not expected an attack this early, and indeed White is able to exert a reasonable amount of pressure on Black, but ultimately the attack fades away, albeit with an interesting position for both sides
This was the reason I wouldn't have considered Bxh7 as an option - Black simply gets rid of this piece with Bxg5... in fact, it wins a piece (White's second sac) Well... not exactly...

An alternative would have been Kg8, but this must be better - after Bxg5, I don't like the pressure from White's queen and bishop...

! Now I see what White's plan is, though I have no idea whether he forsaw this back at move 15, or he used this move as a saving grace. White is five points down, and this is the only move that remedies that...
Threatens mate in 3; 20.Rxh6+ Kg8 21.Rh8+ Kg7 22.Qh7#. At this point. there really is only one way to deal with this threat...

... but I don't mind too much - Black's first sac. With the material that White sacrificed to get this attack, I can afford this - in fact, I am still a point up!
White now has a queen and pawn for a bishop, knight and rook - let's see where this goes! :)
